# Fuzz Harness Standards

Fuzz harnesses use libFuzzer to find crashes, memory errors, and edge cases in parsers and input handlers.

## Harness Structure

```c
#include "human/core/json.h"  // or relevant header

int LLVMFuzzerTestOneInput(const uint8_t *data, size_t size) {
    // Parse, validate, or process the fuzzed input
    // Free all allocations — ASan must stay clean
    return 0;
}
```

## Rules

- One harness per parser or input handler
- Always free all allocations — ASan runs during fuzzing
- Never call `exit()`, `abort()`, or `_exit()` from harness code
- Return 0 from `LLVMFuzzerTestOneInput` on all paths
- Keep harnesses small and focused — fuzz one thing per harness

## Build Requirements

- Requires Clang (`cmake --preset fuzz` or `-DCMAKE_C_COMPILER=clang -DHU_ENABLE_FUZZ=ON`)
- Register new harnesses in `CMakeLists.txt` under the `HU_ENABLE_FUZZ` section
- Each harness compiles to its own binary (e.g., `fuzz_json_parse`)

## Corpus

- Add seed inputs in `fuzz/corpus/<harness_name>/`
- Seeds should cover: valid input, edge cases, empty input, maximum-length input
- Corpus directories are committed to the repo

## Running

```bash
cmake --preset fuzz && cmake --build --preset fuzz
./build-fuzz/fuzz_json_parse fuzz/corpus/json/ -max_total_time=60
```
